SIMPLE: induct
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Induct
<hw>In*duct"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Inducted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inducting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>inductus</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>inducere</ets>. See <er>Induce</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring in; to introduce; to usher in.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The independent orator <qex>inducting</qex> himself without
further ceremony into the pulpit.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To introduce, as to a benefice or office; to put in
actual possession of the temporal rights of an ecclesiastical living, or
of any other office, with the customary forms and ceremonies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The prior, when <qex>inducted</qex> into that dignity, took an
oath not to alienate any of their lands.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Burnet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inductance</ent>⟦br⟧
